<subSubSection id="1FE5655FFFE6416BCAD1EF7EFABE2610" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE6416BCAD1EF7EFD862648" blockId="16.[151,1437,1554,1653]" box="[151,564,1554,1581]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE6416BCAD1EF7EFE912649" bold="true" box="[151,291,1554,1580]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">References:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE6416BCB6CEF7FFD862648" author="Naskrecki, P. &amp; Guta, R." box="[298,564,1555,1581]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" pagination="1" refId="ref18246" refString="Naskrecki, P. &amp; Guta, R. (2019) Katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae) of Gorongosa National Park and Central Mozambique. Zootaxa, 4682 (1), 001 - 119. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4682.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">Naskrecki &amp; Guta 2019</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE6416BCA81EF5AFABE2610" blockId="16.[151,1437,1554,1653]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE6416BCA81EF5AFED02635" bold="true" box="[199,354,1590,1616]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina, stridulatory file and song are described and figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE6416BCE02EF5BFAD42634" author="Naskrecki, P. &amp; Guta, R." box="[1092,1382,1591,1617]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" pagination="1" refId="ref18246" refString="Naskrecki, P. &amp; Guta, R. (2019) Katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae) of Gorongosa National Park and Central Mozambique. Zootaxa, 4682 (1), 001 - 119. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4682.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">Naskrecki &amp; Guta (2019)</bibRefCitation>
. The calling song consists of a long sequence of short echemes (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE6416BC96DEF37FC322610" box="[811,896,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1216,1240]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,204,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-23@12.[151,1436,181,1192]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Cosmoderus and Enyaliopsis (figures of E. iaculator based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Cosmoderus femoratus, B Enyaliopsis bloyeti. C Enyaliopsis carolinus, D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus, song type A, E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 (near ephippiatus), song type B, F Enyaliopsis iaculator, G Enyaliopsis jennae, H Enyaliopsis spec. 2 Mpwapwa. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-ms-section)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392733/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Fig. 8F</figureCitation>
; song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE6416BC98EEF37FC4A2610" box="[968,1016,1627,1653]" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">type</typeStatus>
C in 
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE6416BCE73EF37FBCB2610" box="[1077,1145,1626,1653]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,198,1221]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[151,1436,181,1231]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Oscillograms of song types in Hetrodini. Song consisting A of long trills (Cosmoderus femoralis CH8627), B of broken trills (including transitions to long echemes; B1 Spalacomimus talpa, B2 Enyaliopsis jennae, B3 Enyaliopsis ephippiatus) or C of regularly repeated echemes (C1 Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, C2 Eugaster guyoni). 1-min-sections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392721/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="467">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
; see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE6416BCEF6EF37FAB62610" box="[1200,1284,1627,1653]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="16" pageNumber="467" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
)
</paragraph>
